# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: linear-types
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] Linear logic lends itself to many different presentations, explanations, and intuitions.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] Proof-theoretically, it derives from an analysis of classical sequent calculus in which uses of (the structural rules) contraction and weakening are carefully controlled.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] Operationally, this means that logical deduction is no longer merely about an ever-expanding collection of persistent "truths", but also a way of manipulating *resources* that cannot always be duplicated or thrown away at will.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] In terms of simple denotational models, linear logic may be seen as refining the interpretation of intuitionistic logic by replacing cartesian (closed) categories by symmetric monoidal (closed) categories, or the interpretation of classical logic by replacing Boolean algebras by C*-algebras.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] For readers who are familiar with different notations, the following table, compiled by Paoli 2002, compares the notations for linear-logic connectives and constants across several sources.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] The language ${\mathcal {L}}$ of classical propositional linear logic can be defined recursively as follows.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] If $\varphi$ is an atomic formula, then $\varphi ^{\bot }$ is a formula of ${\mathcal {L}}$ .
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] If $\varphi$ and $\psi$ are formulas of ${\mathcal {L}}$ , then $\varphi \otimes \psi$ is too.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] If $\varphi$ and $\psi$ are formulas of ${\mathcal {L}}$ , then $\varphi$ ⅋ $\psi$ is too.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] If $\varphi$ and $\psi$ are formulas of ${\mathcal {L}}$ , then $\varphi \ \&\ \psi$ is too.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] If $\varphi$ and $\psi$ are formulas of ${\mathcal {L}}$ , then $\varphi \oplus \psi$ is too.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] If $\varphi$ is a formula of ${\mathcal {L}}$ , then ${\displaystyle$ is too.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] Here *p* and *p*⊥ range over logical atoms.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] For reasons to be explained below, the connectives ⊗, ⅋, 1, and ⊥ are called *multiplicatives*, the connectives &, ⊕, ⊤, and 0 are called *additives*, and the connectives ! and ? are called *exponentials*.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] Binary connectives ⊗, ⊕, & and ⅋ are associative and commutative; 1 is the unit for ⊗, 0 is the unit for ⊕, ⊥ is the unit for ⅋ and ⊤ is the unit for &.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] Observe that (-)⊥ is an involution, i.e., *A*⊥⊥ = *A* for all propositions.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] *A*⊥ is also called the *linear negation* of *A*.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] The columns of the table suggest another way of classifying the connectives of linear logic, termed ***polarity***: the connectives negated in the left column (⊗, ⊕, 1, 0, !) are called *positive*, while their duals on the right (⅋, &, ⊥, ⊤, ?) are called *negative*; cf. table on the right.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] One way of defining linear logic is as a sequent calculus.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] We use the letters Γ and Δ to range over finite lists of propositions *A*1, ..., *A**n*, also called *contexts*.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] A *sequent* places a context to the left and the right of the turnstile, written Γ $\vdash$ Δ.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] Intuitively, the sequent asserts that the conjunction of Γ entails the disjunction of Δ (though we mean the "multiplicative" conjunction and disjunction, as explained below).
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] Girard describes classical linear logic using only *one-sided* sequents (where the left-hand context is empty), and we follow here that more economical presentation.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] This is possible because any premises to the left of a turnstile can always be moved to the other side and dualised.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] We now give inference rules describing how to build proofs of sequents.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] Note that we do **not** add the structural rules of weakening and contraction, because we do care about the absence of propositions in a sequent, and the number of copies present.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] The cut rule can be seen as a way of composing proofs, and initial sequents serve as the units for composition.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] In a certain sense these rules are redundant: as we introduce additional rules for building proofs below, we will obtain the property that arbitrary initial sequents can be derived from atomic initial sequents, and that whenever a sequent is provable it can be given a cut-free proof.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] Now, we explain the connectives by giving *logical rules*.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] Typically in sequent calculus one gives both "right-rules" and "left-rules" for each connective, essentially describing two modes of reasoning about propositions involving that connective (e.g., verification and falsification).
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] In a one-sided presentation, one instead makes use of negation: the right-rules for a connective (say ⅋) effectively play the role of left-rules for its dual (⊗).
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] So, we should expect a certain "harmony" between the rule(s) for a connective and the rule(s) for its dual.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] Observe that the rules for multiplicative conjunction and disjunction are admissible for plain *conjunction* and *disjunction* under a classical interpretation (i.e., they are admissible rules in LK).
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] Observe that the rules for additive conjunction and disjunction are again admissible under a classical interpretation.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] The exponentials are used to give controlled access to weakening and contraction.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] This situation is remedied in alternative presentations of CLL (e.g., the LU presentation).
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] Linear distributions are fundamental in the proof theory of linear logic.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] The consequences of this map were first investigated in Cockett & Seely (1997) and called a "weak distribution".
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] In subsequent work it was renamed to "linear distribution" to reflect the fundamental connection to linear logic.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] Both intuitionistic and classical implication can be recovered from linear implication by inserting exponentials: intuitionistic implication is encoded as !*A* ⊸ *B*, while classical implication can be encoded as !?*A* ⊸ ?*B* or !*A* ⊸ ?!*B* (or a variety of alternative possible translations).
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] The idea is that exponentials allow us to use a formula as many times as we need, which is always possible in classical and intuitionistic logic.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] Formally, there exists a translation of formulas of intuitionistic logic to formulas of linear logic in a way that guarantees that the original formula is provable in intuitionistic logic if and only if the translated formula is provable in linear logic.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] Using the Gödel–Gentzen negative translation, we can thus embed classical first-order logic into linear first-order logic.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] Introduced by Jean-Yves Girard, proof nets have been created to avoid the *bureaucracy*, that is all the things that make two derivations different in the logical point of view, but not in a "moral" point of view.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] The goal of proof nets is to make them identical by creating a graphical representation of them.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] Multiple distinct semantics have been developed for linear logic, reflecting its complex nature as a resource-sensitive logical system.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] Unlike classical or intuitionistic logic, linear logic distinguishes between different ways of combining formulas and treats assumptions as finite resources that are consumed during proof rather than being endlessly reproducible.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] An interactive model that interprets formulas as games and proofs as strategies.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] A model that interprets proofs as mathematical objects.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] The algebraic semantics of linear logic is that of quantales.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] In linguistics, linear logic models grammatical parsing as deduction.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] In that circumstance, a valid parse tree corresponds to proving the existence of a sentence using implication rules encoding the grammar.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] Tony Hoare (1985) used purchases at a vending machine to illustrate the logic, and culinary transactions have become the traditional example to describe use of the connectives.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] depending on if implication or par is taken to be the primitive connective.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] Different courses are then conjoined using tensor, as a purchased meal is guaranteed to consist of both.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] indicating that the customer must choose either a soup or a salad.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] The entailment relation in full CLL is undecidable.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] Different intuitionistic variants of linear logic have been considered.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] When based on a single-conclusion sequent calculus presentation, like in ILL (Intuitionistic Linear Logic), the connectives ⅋, ⊥, and ? are absent, and linear implication is treated as a primitive connective.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] In FILL (Full Intuitionistic Linear Logic) the connectives ⅋, ⊥, and ? are present, linear implication is a primitive connective and, similarly to what happens in intuitionistic logic, all connectives (except linear negation) are independent.
[src:linear-types/linear-logic] There are also first- and higher-order extensions of linear logic, whose formal development is somewhat standard (see first-order logic and higher-order logic).
[src:linear-types/region-based-memory-management] In computer science, **region-based memory management** is a type of memory management in which each allocated object is assigned to a **region**.
[src:linear-types/region-based-memory-management] A region, also called a **partition**, **subpool**, **zone**, **arena**, **area**, or **memory context**, is a collection of allocated objects that can be efficiently reallocated or deallocated all at once.
[src:linear-types/region-based-memory-management] Memory allocators using region-based managements are often called **area allocators**, and when they work by only "bumping" a single pointer, as **bump allocators**.
[src:linear-types/region-based-memory-management] Like stack allocation, regions facilitate allocation and deallocation of memory with low overhead; but they are more flexible, allowing objects to live longer than the stack frame in which they were allocated.
[src:linear-types/region-based-memory-management] In typical implementations, all objects in a region are allocated in a single contiguous range of memory addresses, similarly to how stack frames are typically allocated.
[src:linear-types/region-based-memory-management] In OS/360 and successors, the concept applies at two levels; each job runs within a contiguous partition or region.
[src:linear-types/region-based-memory-management] Storage allocation requests specify a subpool, and the application can free an entire subpool.
[src:linear-types/region-based-memory-management] Storage for a subpool is allocated from the region or partition in blocks that are a multiple of 2 KiB or 4 KiB that generally are not contiguous.
[src:linear-types/region-based-memory-management] As a simple example, consider the following C++ code, which implements a simple compile-time arena, and a simple data type consisting of a string and an integer value.
[src:linear-types/region-based-memory-management] Simple explicit regions are straightforward to implement; the following description is based on the work of Hanson.
[src:linear-types/region-based-memory-management] Each region is implemented as a linked list of large blocks of memory; each block should be large enough to serve many allocations.
[src:linear-types/region-based-memory-management] The current block maintains a pointer to the next free position in the block, and if the block is filled, a new one is allocated and added to the list.
[src:linear-types/region-based-memory-management] When the region is deallocated, the next-free-position pointer is reset to the beginning of the first block, and the list of blocks can be reused for the next allocated region.
[src:linear-types/region-based-memory-management] Alternatively, when a region is deallocated, its list of blocks can be appended to a global freelist from which other regions may later allocate new blocks.
[src:linear-types/region-based-memory-management] With either case of this simple scheme, it is not possible to deallocate individual objects in regions.
[src:linear-types/region-based-memory-management] The overall cost per allocated byte of this scheme is very low; almost all allocations involve only a comparison and an update to the next-free-position pointer.
[src:linear-types/region-based-memory-management] Deallocating a region is a constant-time operation, and is done rarely.
[src:linear-types/region-based-memory-management] Unlike in typical garbage collection systems, there is no need to tag data with its type.
[src:linear-types/region-based-memory-management] The basic concept of regions is very old, first appearing as early as 1967 in Douglas T.
[src:linear-types/region-based-memory-management] Ross's AED Free Storage Package, in which memory was partitioned into a hierarchy of zones; each zone had its own allocator, and a zone could be freed all-at-once, making zones usable as regions.
[src:linear-types/region-based-memory-management] In 1976, the PL/I standard included the AREA data type.
[src:linear-types/region-based-memory-management] In 1990, Hanson demonstrated that explicit regions in C (which he called arenas) could achieve time performance per allocated byte superior to even the fastest-known heap allocation mechanism.
[src:linear-types/region-based-memory-management] Explicit regions were instrumental in the design of some early C-based software projects, including the Apache HTTP Server, which calls them pools, and the PostgreSQL database management system, which calls them memory contexts.
[src:linear-types/region-based-memory-management] Like traditional heap allocation, these schemes do not provide memory safety; it is possible for a programmer to access a region after it is deallocated through a dangling pointer, or to forget to deallocate a region, causing a memory leak.
[src:linear-types/region-based-memory-management] The compiler is able to do this in such a way that it can guarantee dangling pointers and leaks do not occur.
[src:linear-types/region-based-memory-management] In an early work by Ruggieri and Murtagh, a region is created at the beginning of each function and deallocated at the end.
[src:linear-types/region-based-memory-management] They then use data flow analysis to determine a lifetime for each static allocation expression, and assign it to the youngest region that contains its entire lifetime.
[src:linear-types/region-based-memory-management] Due to this syntactic structure, regions are *nested*, meaning that if $r_{2}$ is created after $r_{1}$ , it must also be deallocated before $r_{1}$ ; the result is a *stack* of regions.
[src:linear-types/region-based-memory-management] Moreover, regions must be deallocated in the same function in which they are created.
[src:linear-types/region-based-memory-management] These restrictions were relaxed by Aiken et al.
[src:linear-types/region-based-memory-management] This work was completed in 1995 and integrated into the ML Kit, a version of ML based on region allocation in place of garbage collection.
[src:linear-types/region-based-memory-management] This permitted a direct comparison between the two on medium-sized test programs, yielding widely varying results ("between 10 times faster and four times slower") depending on how "region-friendly" the program was; compile times, however, were on the order of minutes.
[src:linear-types/region-based-memory-management] The ML Kit was eventually scaled to large applications with two additions: a scheme for separate compilation of modules, and a hybrid technique combining region inference with tracing garbage collection.
[src:linear-types/region-based-memory-management] Systems using regions may experience issues where regions become very large before they are deallocated and contain a large proportion of dead data; these are commonly called "leaks" (even though they are eventually freed).
[src:linear-types/region-based-memory-management] Eliminating leaks may involve restructuring the program, typically by introducing new, shorter-lifetime regions.
[src:linear-types/region-based-memory-management] Debugging this type of problem is especially difficult in systems using region inference, where the programmer must understand the underlying inference algorithm, or examine the verbose intermediate representation, to diagnose the issue.
[src:linear-types/region-based-memory-management] Tracing garbage collectors are more effective at deallocating this type of data in a timely manner without program changes; this was one justification for hybrid region/GC systems.
[src:linear-types/region-based-memory-management] On the other hand, tracing garbage collectors can also exhibit subtle leaks, if references are retained to data which will never be used again.
[src:linear-types/region-based-memory-management] Region-based memory management works best when the number of regions is relatively small and each contains many objects; programs that contain many sparse regions will exhibit internal fragmentation, leading to wasted memory and a time overhead for region management.
[src:linear-types/region-based-memory-management] Again, in the presence of region inference this problem can be more difficult to diagnose.
[src:linear-types/region-based-memory-management] As mentioned above, RC uses a hybrid of regions and reference counting, limiting the overhead of reference counting since references internal to regions don't require counts to be updated when they're modified.
[src:linear-types/region-based-memory-management] Similarly, some *mark-region* hybrid methods combine tracing garbage collection with regions; these function by dividing the heap into regions, performing a mark-sweep pass in which any regions containing live objects are marked, and then freeing any unmarked regions.
[src:linear-types/region-based-memory-management] These require continual defragmentation to remain effective.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] In computer programming, **resource management** refers to techniques for managing resources (components with limited availability).
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] Computer programs may manage their own resources by using features exposed by programming languages (Elder, Jackson & Liblit (2008) is a survey article contrasting different approaches), or may elect to manage them by a host – an operating system or virtual machine – or another program.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] Host-based management is known as *resource tracking,* and consists of cleaning up resource leaks: terminating access to resources that have been acquired but not released after use.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] This is known as *reclaiming* resources, and is analogous to garbage collection for memory.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] On many systems, the operating system reclaims resources after the process makes the exit system call.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] The omission of releasing a resource when a program has finished using it is known as a resource leak, and is an issue in sequential computing.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] Multiple processes wish to access a limited resource can be an issue in concurrent computing, and is known as resource contention.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] Resource management seeks to control access in order to prevent both of these situations.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] Formally, resource management (preventing resource leaks) consists of ensuring that a resource is released if and only if it is successfully acquired.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] This general problem can be abstracted as "*before,* *body,* and *after*" code, which normally are executed in this order, with the condition that the *after* code is called if and only if the *before* code successfully completes, regardless of whether the *body* code executes successfully or not.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] This is also known as *execute around* or a *code sandwich,* and occurs in various other contexts, such as a temporary change of program state, or tracing entry and exit into a subroutine.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] However, resource management is the most commonly cited application.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] In aspect-oriented programming, such execute around logic is a form of *advice*.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] In the terminology of control flow analysis, resource release must postdominate successful resource acquisition; failure to ensure this is a bug, and a code path that violates this condition causes a resource leak.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] Resource leaks are often minor problems, generally not crashing the program, but instead causing some slowdown to the program or the overall system.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] However, they may cause crashes – either the program itself or other programs – due to *resource exhaustion:* if the system runs out of resources, acquisition requests fail.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] This can present a security bug if an attack can cause resource exhaustion.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] Resource leaks may happen under regular program flow – such as simply forgetting to release a resource – or only in exceptional circumstances, such as when a resource is not released if there is an exception in another part of the program.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] Resource leaks are very frequently caused by early exit from a subroutine, either by a `return` statement, or an exception raised either by the subroutine itself, or a deeper subroutine that it calls.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] While resource release due to return statements can be handled by carefully releasing within the subroutine before the return, exceptions cannot be handled without some additional language facility that guarantees that release code is executed.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] More subtly, successful resource acquisition must dominate resource release, as otherwise the code will try to release a resource it has not acquired.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] The consequences of such an incorrect release range from being silently ignored to crashing the program or unpredictable behavior.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] These bugs generally manifest rarely, as they require resource allocation to first fail, which is generally an exceptional case.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] Further, the consequences may not be serious, as the program may already be crashing due to failure to acquire an essential resource.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] However, these can prevent recovery from the failure, or turn an orderly shutdown into a disorderly shutdown.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] In computer science, resource contention refers to a conflict that arises when multiple entities attempt to access a shared resource, like random access memory, disk storage, cache memory, internal buses, or external network devices.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] Memory can be treated as a resource, but memory management is usually considered separately, primarily because memory allocation and deallocation is significantly more frequent than acquisition and release of other resources, such as file handles.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] Memory managed by an *external* system has similarities to both (internal) memory management (since it is memory) and resource management (since it is managed by an external system).
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] Examples include memory managed via native code and used from Java (via Java Native Interface); and objects in the Document Object Model (DOM), used from JavaScript.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] In both these cases, the memory manager (garbage collector) of the runtime environment (virtual machine) is unable to manage the external memory (there is no shared memory management), and thus the external memory is treated as a resource, and managed analogously.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] However, cycles between systems (JavaScript referring to the DOM, referring back to JavaScript) can make management difficult or impossible.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] Lexical management, when applicable, allows a better separation of concerns and is less error-prone.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] This is correct if the intervening `...` code does not contain an early exit (`return`), the language does not have exceptions, and `open` is guaranteed to succeed.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] However, it causes a resource leak if there is a return or exception, and causes an incorrect release of unacquired resource if `open` can fail.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] There are two more fundamental problems: the acquisition-release pair is not adjacent (the release code must be written far from the acquisition code), and resource management is not encapsulated – the programmer must manually ensure that they are always paired.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] In combination, these mean that acquisition and release must be explicitly paired, but cannot be placed together, thus making it easy for these to not be paired correctly.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] This ensures correct release even if there is a return within the body or an exception thrown.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] Further, note that the acquisition occurs *before* the `try` clause, ensuring that the `finally` clause is only executed if the `open` code succeeds (without throwing an exception), assuming that "no exception" means "success" (as is the case for `open` in Python).
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] While this ensures correct resource management, it fails to provide adjacency or encapsulation.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] There are many variations in the implementation, and there are also significantly different approaches.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] The most common approach to resource management across languages is to use unwind protection, which is called when execution exits a scope – by execution running off the end of the block, returning from within the block, or an exception being thrown.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] This works for stack-managed resources, and is implemented in many languages, including C#, Common Lisp, Java, Python, Ruby, and Scheme.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] The main problems with this approach is that the release code (most commonly in a `finally` clause) may be very distant from the acquisition code (it lacks *adjacency*), and that the acquisition and release code must always be paired by the caller (it lacks *encapsulation*).
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] An alternative, more imperative approach, is to write asynchronous code in direct style: acquire a resource, and then in the next line have a *deferred* release, which is called when the scope is exited – synchronous acquisition followed by asynchronous release.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] This originated in C++ as the ScopeGuard class, by Andrei Alexandrescu and Petru Marginean in 2000, with improvements by Joshua Lehrer, and has direct language support in D via the `scope` keyword (ScopeGuardStatement), where it is one approach to exception safety, in addition to RAII (see below).
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] It has also been included in Go, as the `defer` statement.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] This approach lacks encapsulation – one must explicitly match acquisition and release – but avoids having to create an object for each resource (code-wise, avoid writing a class for each type of resource).
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] In object-oriented programming, resources are encapsulated within objects that use them, such as a `file` object having a field whose value is a file descriptor (or more general file handle).
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] This allows the object to use and manage the resource without users of the object needing to do so.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] However, there is a wide variety of ways that objects and resources can be related.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] Firstly, there is the question of ownership: does an object *have* a resource?
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] Most common is to acquire a resource during object creation, and then explicitly release it via an instance method, commonly called `dispose`.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] This is analogous to traditional file management (acquire during `open`, release by explicit `close`), and is known as the dispose pattern.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] This is the basic approach used in several major modern object-oriented languages, including Java, C# and Python, and these languages have additional constructs to automate resource management.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] However, even in these languages, more complex object relationships result in more complex resource management, as discussed below.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] A natural approach is to make holding a resource be a class invariant: resources are acquired during object creation (specifically initialization), and released during object destruction (specifically finalization).
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] This is known as Resource Acquisition Is Initialization (RAII), and ties resource management to object lifetime, ensuring that live objects have all necessary resources.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] Other approaches do not make holding the resource a class invariant, and thus objects may not have necessary resources (because they've not been acquired yet, have already been released, or are being managed externally), resulting in errors such as trying to read from a closed file.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] This approach ties resource management to memory management (specifically object management), so if there are no memory leaks (no object leaks), there are no resource leaks.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] RAII works naturally for heap-managed resources, not only stack-managed resources, and is composable: resources held by objects in arbitrarily complicated relationships (a complicated object graph) are released transparently simply by object destruction (so long as this is done properly!).
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] Firstly, because resources are expensive, it is desirable to release them promptly, so objects holding resources should be destroyed as soon as they become garbage (are no longer in use).
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] However, most modern automatic memory management is non-deterministic, making no guarantees that objects will be destroyed promptly or even at all!
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] This is because it is cheaper to leave some garbage allocated than to precisely collect each object immediately on its becoming garbage.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] Secondly, releasing resources during object destruction means that an object must have a *finalizer* (in deterministic memory management known as a *destructor*) – the object cannot simply be deallocated – which significantly complicates and slows garbage collection.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] When multiple objects rely on a single resource, resource management can be complicated.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] A fundamental question is whether a "has a" relationship is one of *owning* another object (object composition), or *viewing* another object (object aggregation).
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] A common case is when one two objects are chained, as in pipe and filter pattern, the delegation pattern, the decorator pattern, or the adapter pattern.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] If the second object (which is not used directly) holds a resource, is the first object (which is used directly) responsible for managing the resource?
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] This is generally answered identically to whether the first object *owns* the second object: if so, then the owning object is also responsible for resource management ("having a resource" is transitive), while if not, then it is not.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] Further, a single object may "have" several other objects, owning some and viewing others.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] Both cases are commonly found, and conventions differ.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] In object aggregation, nothing needs to be done by the viewing object, as it is not responsible for the resource.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] For example, in the Java Class Library, `Reader#close()` closes the underlying stream, and these can be chained.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] For example, a `BufferedReader` may contain a `InputStreamReader`, which in turn contains a `FileInputStream`, and calling `close` on the `BufferedReader` in turn closes the `InputStreamReader`, which in turn closes the `FileInputStream`, which in turn releases the system file resource.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] By contrast, in Python, a csv.reader does not own the `file` that it is reading, so there is no need (and it is not possible) to close the reader, and instead the `file` itself must be closed.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] Various mechanisms exist to allow greater control of resource management.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] For example, in the Google Closure Library, the `goog.Disposable` class provides a `registerDisposable` method to register other objects to be disposed with this object, together with various lower-level instance and class methods to manage disposal.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] In structured programming, stack resource management is done simply by nesting code sufficiently to handle all cases.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] This requires only a single return at the end of the code, and can result in heavily nested code if many resources must be acquired, which is considered an anti-pattern by some – the *Arrow Anti Pattern,* due to the triangular shape from the successive nesting.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] One other approach, which allows early return but consolidates cleanup in one place, is to have a single exit return of a function, preceded by cleanup code, and to use goto to jump to the cleanup before exit.
[src:linear-types/resource-management-computing] This is infrequently seen in modern code, but occurs in some uses of C.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Rust supports multiple programming paradigms.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] It was influenced by ideas from functional programming, including immutability, higher-order functions, algebraic data types, and pattern matching.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] It also supports object-oriented programming via structs, enums, traits, and methods.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Rust enforces memory safety (i.e., that all references point to valid memory) without a conventional garbage collector; instead, memory safety errors and data races are prevented by the "borrow checker", which tracks the object lifetime of references at compile time.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Software developer Graydon Hoare created Rust in 2006 while working at Mozilla, which officially sponsored the project in 2009.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The first stable release, Rust 1.0, was published in May 2015.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The project has been sponsored by the Rust Foundation since February 2021.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Rust has been adopted by many software projects, especially web services and system software.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] It has been studied academically and has a growing community of developers.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Rust began as a personal project by Mozilla employee Graydon Hoare in 2006.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] According to *MIT Technology Review*, he started the project due to his frustration with a broken elevator in his apartment building whose software had crashed, and named the language after the group of fungi of the same name that is "over-engineered for survival".
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] During the time period between 2006 and 2009, Rust was not publicized to others at Mozilla and was written in Hoare's free time; Hoare began speaking about the language around 2009 after a small group at Mozilla became interested in the project.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Hoare cited languages from the 1970s, 1980s, and 1990s as influences — including CLU, BETA, Mesa, NIL, Erlang, Newsqueak, Napier, Hermes, Sather, Alef, and Limbo.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] During the early years, the Rust compiler was written in about 38,000 lines of OCaml.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Early Rust contained several features no longer present today, including explicit object-oriented programming via an `obj` keyword and a typestates system for variable state changes, such as going from uninitialized to initialized.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Mozilla officially sponsored the Rust project in 2009.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Brendan Eich and other executives, intrigued by the possibility of using Rust for a safe web browser engine, placed engineers on the project including Patrick Walton, Niko Matsakis, Felix Klock, and Manish Goregaokar.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] A conference room taken by the project developers was dubbed "the nerd cave," with a sign placed outside the door.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] During this time period, work had shifted from the initial OCaml compiler to a self-hosting compiler (*i.e.*, written in Rust) targeting LLVM.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The ownership system was in place by 2010.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The Rust logo was developed in 2011 based on a bicycle chainring.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Rust 0.1 became the first public release on January 20, 2012 for Windows, Linux, and MacOS.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The early 2010s witnessed increasing involvement from full-time engineers at Mozilla and open source volunteers outside Mozilla.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The years from 2012 to 2015 were marked by substantial changes to the Rust type system.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Memory management through the ownership system was gradually consolidated and expanded.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] By 2013, the garbage collector was rarely used, and was removed in favor of the ownership system.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Other features were removed in order to simplify the language, including typestates, the `pure` keyword, various specialized pointer types, and syntax support for channels.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] According to Steve Klabnik, Rust was influenced during this period by developers coming from C++ (e.g., low-level performance of features), scripting languages (e.g., Cargo and package management), and functional programming (e.g., type systems development).
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Graydon Hoare stepped down from Rust in 2013.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] After Hoare's departure, it evolved organically under a federated governance structure, with a "core team" of initially six people, and around 30-40 developers total across various other teams.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] A Request for Comments (RFC) process for new language features was added in March 2014.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The core team would grow to nine people by 2016 with over 1600 RFCs.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Dobb's Journal* in January 2014, while Rust was "widely viewed as a remarkably elegant language", adoption slowed because it radically changed from version to version.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Rust development at this time focused on finalizing features for version 1.0 so that it could begin promising backward compatibility.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Six years after Mozilla's sponsorship, Rust 1.0 was published and became the first stable release on May 15, 2015.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] A year later, the Rust compiler had accumulated over 1,400 contributors, and there were over 5,000 third-party libraries published on the Rust package management website Crates.io.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The development of the Servo browser engine continued in parallel with Rust, jointly funded by Mozilla and Samsung.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The teams behind the two projects worked in close collaboration; new features in Rust were tested out by the Servo team, and new features in Servo were used to give feedback back to the Rust team.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The first version of Servo was released in 2016.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The Firefox web browser shipped with Rust code as of 2016 (version 45), but components of Servo did not appear in Firefox until September 2017 (version 57) as part of the Gecko and Quantum projects.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Improvements were made to the Rust toolchain ecosystem during the years following 1.0 including Rustfmt, integrated development environment integration, and a regular compiler testing and release cycle.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Rust's community gained a code of conduct and an IRC chat for discussion.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The earliest known adoption outside of Mozilla was by individual projects at Samsung, Facebook (now Meta Platforms), Dropbox, and Tilde, Inc., the company behind ember.js.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Engineers cited performance, lack of a garbage collector, safety, and pleasantness of working in the language as reasons for the adoption.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Amazon developers cited a finding by Portuguese researchers that Rust code used less energy compared to similar code written in Java.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] In August 2020, Mozilla laid off 250 of its 1,000 employees worldwide, as part of a corporate restructuring caused by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The event raised concerns about the future of Rust.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] In the following week, the Rust Core Team acknowledged the severe impact of the layoffs and announced that plans for a Rust foundation were underway.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The first goal of the foundation would be to take ownership of all trademarks and domain names and to take financial responsibility for their costs.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] On February 8, 2021, the formation of the Rust Foundation was announced by five founding companies: Amazon Web Services, Google, Huawei, Microsoft, and Mozilla.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The foundation would provide financial support for Rust developers in the form of grants and server funding.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] In a blog post published on April 6, 2021, Google announced support for Rust within the Android Open Source Project as an alternative to C/C++.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] On November 22, 2021, the Moderation Team, which was responsible for enforcing the community code of conduct, announced their resignation "in protest of the Core Team placing themselves unaccountable to anyone but themselves".
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] In May 2022, members of the Rust leadership council posted a public response to the incident.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The Rust Foundation posted a draft for a new trademark policy on April 6, 2023, which resulted in widespread negative reactions from Rust users and contributors.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The trademark policy included rules for how the Rust logo and name could be used.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Rust's syntax is similar to that of C and C++, although many of its features were influenced by functional programming languages such as OCaml.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Hoare has described Rust as targeted at frustrated C++ developers.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Below is a "Hello, World!" program in Rust.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The `fn` keyword denotes a function, and the `println!` macro (see § Macros) prints the message to standard output.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Statements in Rust are separated by semicolons.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Variables in Rust are defined through the `let` keyword.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The example below assigns a value to the variable with name `foo` of type `i32` and outputs its value; the type annotation `: i32` can be omitted.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Variables are immutable by default, unless the `mut` keyword is added.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The following example uses `//`, which denotes the start of a comment.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Multiple `let` expressions can define multiple variables with the same name, known as variable shadowing.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing allows transforming variables without having to name the variables differently.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing is also possible for values of different types.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] A *block expression* is delimited by curly brackets.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] An `if` conditional expression executes code based on whether the given value is `true`.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] `else` can be used for when the value evaluates to `false`, and `else if` can be used for combining multiple expressions.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] `while` can be used to repeat a block of code while a condition is met.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] For loops in Rust loop over elements of a collection.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] `for` expressions work over any iterator type.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] In the above code, `4..=10` is a value of type `Range` which implements the `Iterator` trait.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The code within the curly braces is applied to each element returned by the iterator.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Iterators can be combined with functions over iterators like `map`, `filter`, and `sum`.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] More generally, the `loop` keyword allows repeating a portion of code until a `break` occurs.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] `break` may optionally exit the loop with a value.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] In the case of nested loops, labels denoted by `'label_name` can be used to break an outer loop rather than the innermost loop.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The `match` and `if let` expressions can be used for pattern matching.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Rust is strongly typed and statically typed, meaning that the types of all variables must be known at compilation time.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Assigning a value of a particular type to a differently typed variable causes a compilation error.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Type inference is used to determine the type of variables if unspecified.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The type `()`, called the "unit type" in Rust, is a concrete type that has exactly one value.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] It occupies no memory (as it represents the absence of value).
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] All functions that do not have an indicated return type implicitly return `()`.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] It is similar to `void` in other C-style languages; however, `void` denotes the absence of a type and cannot have any value.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The default integer type is `i32`, and the default floating point type is `f64`.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] If the type of a literal number is not explicitly provided, it is either inferred from the context or the default type is used.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Integer types in Rust are named based on the signedness and the number of bits the type takes.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] For example, `i32` is a signed integer that takes 32 bits of storage, whereas `u8` is unsigned and only takes 8 bits of storage.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] `isize` and `usize` take storage depending on the memory address bus width of the compilation target.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] For example, when building for 32-bit targets, both types will take up 32 bits of space.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals are in base-10, but different radices are supported with prefixes, for example, `0b11` for binary numbers, `0o567` for octals, and `0xDB` for hexadecimals.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals default to `i32` as its type.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Suffixes such as `4u32` can be used to explicitly set the type of a literal.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Byte literals such as `b'X'` are available to represent the ASCII value (as a `u8`) of a specific character.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The Boolean type is referred to as `bool` which can take a value of either `true` or `false`.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] A `char` takes up 32 bits of space and represents a Unicode scalar value: a Unicode codepoint that is not a surrogate.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] IEEE 754 floating point numbers are supported with `f32` for single precision floats and `f64` for double precision floats.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Compound types can contain multiple values.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Tuples are fixed-size lists that can contain values whose types can be different.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Arrays are fixed-size lists whose values are of the same type.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Rust's ownership system consists of rules that ensure memory safety without using a garbage collector.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] At compile time, each value must be attached to a variable called the *owner* of that value, and every value must have exactly one owner.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Values are moved between different owners through assignment or passing a value as a function parameter.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Values can also be *borrowed,* meaning they are temporarily passed to a different function before being returned to the owner.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Because of these ownership rules, Rust types are known as *affine types*, meaning each value may be used at most once.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] This enforces a form of software fault isolation as the owner of a value is solely responsible for its correctness and deallocation.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] When a value goes out of scope, it is *dropped* by running its destructor.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The destructor may be programmatically defined through implementing the `Drop` trait.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] This helps manage resources such as file handles, network sockets, and locks, since when objects are dropped, the resources associated with them are closed or released automatically.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Object lifetime refers to the period of time during which a reference is valid; that is, the time between the object creation and destruction.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] These *lifetimes* are implicitly associated with all Rust reference types.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] While often inferred, they can also be indicated explicitly with named lifetime parameters (often denoted `'a`, `'b`, and so on).
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] A value's lifetime in Rust is inferred from the set of locations in the source code (i.e., function, line, and column numbers) for which a variable is valid.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] For example, a reference to a local variable has a lifetime from the expression it is declared in up until the last use of it.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The borrow checker in the Rust compiler then enforces that references are only used in the locations of the source code where the associated lifetime is valid.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] In the example above, storing a reference to variable `x` in `r` is valid, as variable `x` has a longer lifetime (`'a`) than variable `r` (`'b`).
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Since the lifetime of the referenced variable (`'b`) is shorter than the lifetime of the variable holding the reference (`'a`), the borrow checker errors, preventing `x` from being used from outside its scope.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Lifetimes can be indicated using explicit *lifetime parameters* on function arguments.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] In the compiler, ownership and lifetimes work together to prevent memory safety issues such as dangling pointers.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] User-defined types are created with the `struct` or `enum` keywords.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The `struct` keyword is used to denote a record type that groups multiple related values.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] `enum`s can take on different variants at runtime, with their capabilities similar to algebraic data types found in functional programming languages.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Both records and enum variants can contain fields with different types.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Alternative names, or aliases, for the same type can be defined with the `type` keyword.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The `impl` keyword can define methods for a user-defined type.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Data and functions are defined separately.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Implementations fulfill a role similar to that of classes within other languages.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The Rust standard library defines and implements many widely used custom data types, including core data structures such as `Vec`, `Option`, and `HashMap`, as well as smart pointer types.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Rust provides a way to exclude most of the standard library using the attribute `#![no_std]`, for applications such as embedded devices.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Internally, the standard library is divided into three parts, `core`, `alloc`, and `std`, where `std` and `alloc` are excluded by `#![no_std]`.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Similarly, Rust's result type `Result<T, E>` holds either a successfully computed value (the `Ok` variant) or an error (the `Err` variant).
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Like `Option`, the use of `Result` means that the inner value cannot be used directly; programmers must use a `match` expression, syntactic sugar such as `?` (the "try" operator), or an explicit `unwrap` assertion to access it.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Both `Option` and `Result` are used throughout the standard library and are a fundamental part of Rust's explicit approach to handling errors and missing data.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The `&` and `&mut` reference types are guaranteed to not be null and point to valid memory.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The raw pointer types `*const` and `*mut` opt out of the safety guarantees, thus they may be null or invalid; however, it is impossible to dereference them unless the code is explicitly declared unsafe through the use of an `unsafe` block.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Unlike dereferencing, the creation of raw pointers is allowed inside safe Rust code.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Rust provides no implicit type conversion (coercion) between most primitive types.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] But, explicit type conversion (casting) can be performed using the `as` keyword.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Rust supports polymorphism through traits, generic functions, and trait objects.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The example above includes a method `is_zero` which provides a default implementation that may be overridden when implementing the trait.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] In the examples above, `Num: Zero` as well as `where Self: PartialEq` are trait bounds that constrain the type to only allow types that implement `Zero` or `PartialEq`.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Within a trait or impl, `Self` refers to the type that the code is implementing.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Generics can be used in functions to allow implementing a behavior for different types without repeating the same code (see bounded parametric polymorphism).
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Generic functions can be written in relation to other generics, without knowing the actual type.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] By default, traits use static dispatch: the compiler monomorphizes the function for each concrete type instance, yielding performance equivalent to type-specific code at the cost of longer compile times and larger binaries.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] When the exact type is not known at compile time, Rust provides trait objects `&dyn Trait` and `Box<dyn Trait>`.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Trait object calls use dynamic dispatch via a lookup table; a trait object is a "fat pointer" carrying both a data pointer and a method table pointer.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] This indirection adds a small runtime cost, but it keeps a single copy of the code and reduces binary size.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Only "object-safe" traits are eligible to be used as trait objects.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] This approach is similar to duck typing, where all data types that implement a given trait can be treated as functionally interchangeable.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] If an element in the list does not implement the `Display` trait, it will cause a compile-time error.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Memory and other resources are instead managed through the "resource acquisition is initialization" convention, with optional reference counting.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Rust provides deterministic management of resources, with very low overhead.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Values are allocated on the stack by default, and all dynamic allocations must be explicit.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The built-in reference types using the `&` symbol do not involve run-time reference counting.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The safety and validity of the underlying pointers are verified at compile time, preventing dangling pointers and other forms of undefined behavior.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Rust's type system separates shared, immutable references of the form `&T` from unique, mutable references of the form `&mut T`.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] A mutable reference can be coerced to an immutable reference, but not vice versa.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Rust's memory safety checks (See #Safety) may be circumvented through the use of `unsafe` blocks.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] This allows programmers to dereference arbitrary raw pointers, call external code, or perform other low-level functionality not allowed by safe Rust.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Some low-level functionality enabled in this way includes volatile memory access, architecture-specific intrinsics, type punning, and inline assembly.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Unsafe code is needed, for example, in the implementation of data structures.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] A frequently cited example is that it is difficult or impossible to implement doubly linked lists in safe Rust.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Programmers using unsafe Rust are considered responsible for upholding Rust's memory and type safety requirements, for example, that no two mutable references exist pointing to the same location.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] If programmers write code that violates these requirements, this results in undefined behavior.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The Rust documentation includes a list of behaviors considered undefined, including accessing dangling or misaligned pointers, or breaking the aliasing rules for references.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Macros allow the generation and transformation of Rust code to reduce repetition.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Macros come in two forms, with *declarative macros* defined through `macro_rules!`, and *procedural macros*, which are defined in separate crates.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] A declarative macro (also called a "macro by example") is a macro, defined using the `macro_rules!` keyword, that uses pattern matching to determine its expansion.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] In this example, the macro named `sum` is defined using the form `macro_rules! sum {` `(...) => { ... } }`.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The first part inside the parentheses of the definition, the macro pattern `( $initial:expr $(, $expr:expr )* $(,)? )` specifies the structure of input it can take.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Here, `$initial:expr` represents the first expression, while `$(, $expr:expr )*` means there can be zero or more additional comma-separated expressions after it.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The trailing `$(,)?` allows the caller to optionally include a final comma without causing an error.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The second part, after the arrow `=>`, describes what code will be generated when the macro is invoked.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] In this case, `$initial $(+ $expr)*` means that the generated code will start with the first expression, followed by a `+` and each of the additional expressions in sequence.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The `*` again means "repeat this pattern zero or more times".
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] This means, when the macro is later called in line 8, as `sum!(1, 2, 3)`, the macro will resolve to `1 + 2 + 3` representing the addition of all of the passed expressions.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Procedural macros are Rust functions that run and modify the compiler's input token stream, before any other components are compiled.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] They are generally more flexible than declarative macros, but are more difficult to maintain due to their complexity.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Rust supports the creation of foreign function interfaces (FFI) through the `extern` keyword.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] A function that uses the C calling convention can be written using `extern "C" fn`.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The `#[repr(C)]` attribute enables deterministic memory layouts for `struct`s and `enum`s for use across FFI boundaries.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] External libraries such as `bindgen` and `cxx` can generate Rust bindings for C/C++.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Safety properties guaranteed by Rust include memory safety, type safety, and data race freedom.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] As described above, these guarantees can be circumvented by using the `unsafe` keyword.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Memory safety includes the absence of dereferences to null, dangling, and misaligned pointers, and the absence of buffer overflows and double free errors.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Memory leaks may occur as a result of creating reference-counted pointers that point at each other (a reference cycle) or can be deliberately created through calling `Box::leak`.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The Rust ecosystem includes its compiler, its standard library, and additional components for software development.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Component installation is typically managed by `rustup`, a Rust toolchain installer developed by the Rust project.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The Rust compiler, `rustc`, compiles Rust code into binaries.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] First, the compiler parses the source code into an AST.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The compiler backend is then invoked as a subcomponent to apply optimizations and translate the resulting IR into object code.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Finally, a linker is used to combine the object(s) into a single executable image.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] rustc uses LLVM as its compiler backend by default, but it also supports using alternative backends such as GCC and Cranelift.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The intention of those alternative backends is to increase platform coverage of Rust or to improve compilation times.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Cargo is Rust's build system and package manager.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] It downloads, compiles, distributes, and uploads packages—called *crates*—that are maintained in an official registry.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] It also acts as a front-end for Clippy and other Rust components.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] By default, Cargo sources its dependencies from the user-contributed registry *crates.io*, but Git repositories, crates in the local filesystem, and other external sources can also be specified as dependencies.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Cargo supports reproducible builds through two metadata files: Cargo.toml and Cargo.lock.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Cargo.toml declares each package used and their version requirements.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Cargo.lock is generated automatically during dependency resolution and records exact versions of all dependencies, including transitive dependencies.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] It formats whitespace and indentation to produce code in accordance with a common style, unless otherwise specified.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] It can be invoked as a standalone program or from a Rust project through Cargo.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Clippy is Rust's built-in linting tool to improve the correctness, performance, and readability of Rust code.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Following Rust 1.0, new features are developed in *nightly* versions, which are released daily.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] During each six-week release cycle, changes to nightly versions are released to beta, while changes from the previous beta version are released to a new stable version.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Every two or three years, a new "edition" is produced.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Editions are released to allow making limited breaking changes, such as promoting `await` to a keyword to support async/await features.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Crates targeting different editions can interoperate with each other, so a crate can upgrade to a new edition even if its callers or its dependencies still target older editions.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Migration to a new edition can be assisted with automated tooling.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Since it performs no garbage collection, Rust is often faster than other memory-safe languages.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Most of Rust's memory safety guarantees impose no runtime overhead, with the notable exception of array indexing which is checked at runtime by default.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The performance impact of array indexing bounds checks varies, but can be significant in some cases.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Many of Rust's features are so-called *zero-cost abstractions*, meaning they are optimized away at compile time and incur no runtime penalty.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The ownership and borrowing system permits zero-copy implementations for some performance-sensitive tasks, such as parsing.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Static dispatch is used by default to eliminate method calls, except for methods called on dynamic trait objects.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The compiler uses inline expansion to eliminate function calls and statically dispatched method invocations.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Unlike C and C++, Rust allows the compiler to reorder struct and enum elements unless a `#[repr(C)]` representation attribute is applied.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] This allows the compiler to produce more efficient code in some cases.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Performance improvements in LLVM carry over to Rust.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] In web services, OpenDNS, a DNS resolution service owned by Cisco, uses Rust internally.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Amazon Web Services uses Rust in "performance-sensitive components" of services.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] In 2019, AWS open-sourced Firecracker, a virtualization solution primarily written in Rust.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Microsoft Azure IoT Edge, a platform used to run Azure services on IoT devices, has components implemented in Rust.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Microsoft also uses Rust to run containerized modules with WebAssembly and Kubernetes.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Cloudflare, a company providing content delivery network services, used Rust to build a new web proxy named Pingora for increased performance and efficiency.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The npm package manager used Rust for its production authentication service in 2019.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] In operating systems, the Linux kernel began introducing experimental support for Rust code in Version 6.1 in late 2022, as part of the Rust for Linux project.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The first drivers written in Rust were included in version 6.8.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] In 2025, kernel developers at the Linux Kernel Developers Summit determined the project to be a success, and Rust usage for kernel code will no longer be considered experimental.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The Android developers used Rust in 2021 to rewrite existing components.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Microsoft has rewritten parts of Windows in Rust.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The r9 project aims to re-implement Plan 9 from Bell Labs in Rust.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Rust has also been used in the development of new operating systems such as Redox, a "Unix-like" operating system and microkernel, Theseus, an experimental operating system with modular state management, and most of Fuchsia.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Rust is used for command-line tools and operating system components such as stratisd, a file system manager and COSMIC, a desktop environment by System76.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] In web development, Deno, a secure runtime for JavaScript and TypeScript, is built on top of V8 using Rust and Tokio.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Other notable adoptions in this space include Ruffle, an open-source SWF emulator, and Polkadot, an open source blockchain and cryptocurrency platform.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Components from the Servo browser engine (funded by Mozilla and Samsung) were incorporated in the Gecko browser engine underlying Firefox.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] In January 2023, Google (Alphabet) announced support for using third party Rust libraries in Chromium.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] In other uses, Discord, an instant messaging software company, rewrote parts of its system in Rust for increased performance in 2020.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] In the same year, Dropbox announced that its file synchronization had been rewritten in Rust.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Facebook (Meta) used Rust to redesign its system that manages source code for internal projects.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] In the 2025 Stack Overflow Developer Survey, 14.8% of respondents had recently done extensive development in Rust.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The survey named Rust the "most admired programming language" annually from 2016 to 2025 (inclusive), as measured by the number of existing developers interested in continuing to work in the language.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] In 2025, 29.2% of developers not currently working in Rust expressed an interest in doing so.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Rust's safety and performance have been investigated in programming languages research.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] In other fields, a journal article published to *Proceedings of the International Astronomical Union* used Rust to simulate multi-planet systems.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] An article published in *Nature* shared stories of bioinformaticians using Rust.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Both articles cited Rust's performance and safety as advantages, and the learning curve as being a primary drawback to Rust adoption.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The 2025 DARPA project TRACTOR aims to automatically translate C to Rust using techniques such as static analysis, dynamic analysis, and large language models.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] According to the *MIT Technology Review*, the Rust community has been seen as "unusually friendly" to newcomers and particularly attracted people from the queer community, partly due to its code of conduct.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] Inclusiveness has been cited as an important factor for some Rust developers.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The official Rust blog collects and publishes demographic data each year.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The **Rust Foundation** is a non-profit membership organization incorporated in United States; it manages the Rust trademark, infrastructure, and assets.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] It was established on February 8, 2021, with five founding corporate members (Amazon Web Services, Huawei, Google, Microsoft, and Mozilla).
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The foundation's board was chaired by Shane Miller, with Ashley Williams as interim executive director.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] In late 2021, Rebecca Rumbul became executive director and CEO.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The Rust project is maintained by 8 top-level *teams* as of November 2025: the leadership council, compiler team, dev tools team, infrastructure team, language team, launching pad, library team, and moderation team.
[src:linear-types/rust-programming-language] The leadership council oversees the project and is formed by representatives among the other teams.
[src:linear-types/substructural-type-system] The Clean programming language makes use of uniqueness types (a variant of linear types) to help support concurrency, input/output, and in-place update of arrays.
[src:linear-types/substructural-type-system] Linear type systems allow references but not aliases.
[src:linear-types/substructural-type-system] To enforce this, a reference goes out of scope after appearing on the right-hand side of an assignment, thus ensuring that only one reference to any object exists at once.
[src:linear-types/substructural-type-system] Note that passing a reference as an argument to a function is a form of assignment, as the function parameter will be assigned the value inside the function, and therefore such use of a reference also causes it to go out of scope.
[src:linear-types/substructural-type-system] The single-reference property makes linear type systems suitable as programming languages for quantum computing, as it reflects the no-cloning theorem of quantum states.
[src:linear-types/substructural-type-system] From the category theory point of view, no-cloning is a statement that there is no diagonal functor which could duplicate states; similarly, from the combinatory logic point of view, there is no K-combinator which can destroy states.
[src:linear-types/substructural-type-system] From the lambda calculus point of view, a variable `x` can appear exactly once in a term.
[src:linear-types/substructural-type-system] Linear type systems are the internal language of closed symmetric monoidal categories, much in the same way that simply typed lambda calculus is the language of Cartesian closed categories.
[src:linear-types/substructural-type-system] More precisely, one may construct functors between the category of linear type systems and the category of closed symmetric monoidal categories.
[src:linear-types/substructural-type-system] The nomenclature offered by substructural type systems is useful to characterize resource management aspects of a language.
[src:linear-types/substructural-type-system] Resource management is the aspect of language safety concerned with ensuring that each allocated resource is deallocated exactly once.
[src:linear-types/substructural-type-system] Thus, **the resource interpretation** is only concerned with uses that transfer ownership – *moving*, where ownership is the responsibility to free the resource.
[src:linear-types/substructural-type-system] Uses that don't transfer ownership – *borrowing* – are not in scope of this interpretation, but *lifetime semantics* further restrict these uses to be between allocation and deallocation.
[src:linear-types/substructural-type-system] Under the resource interpretation, an *affine* type cannot be spent more than once.
[src:linear-types/substructural-type-system] In other words, an affine type system can express the typestate pattern: Functions can consume and return an object wrapped in different types, acting like state transitions in a state machine that stores its state as a type in the caller's context – a *typestate*.
[src:linear-types/substructural-type-system] An API can exploit this to statically enforce that its functions are called in a correct order.
[src:linear-types/substructural-type-system] What Rust is not able to express is a coin type that cannot go out of scope – that would take a linear type.
[src:linear-types/substructural-type-system] Under the resource interpretation, a *linear* type not only *can* be moved, like an affine type, but *must* be moved – going out of scope is an invalid program.
[src:linear-types/substructural-type-system] An attraction with linear types is that destructors become regular functions that can take arguments, can fail and so on.
[src:linear-types/substructural-type-system] This may for example avoid the need to keep state that is only used for destruction.
[src:linear-types/substructural-type-system] A general advantage of passing function dependencies explicitly is that the order of function calls – destruction order – becomes statically verifiable in terms of the arguments' lifetimes.
[src:linear-types/substructural-type-system] Compared to internal references, this does not require lifetime annotations as in Rust.
[src:linear-types/substructural-type-system] As with manual resource management, a practical problem is that any early return, as is typical of error handling, must achieve the same cleanup.
[src:linear-types/substructural-type-system] This becomes pedantic in languages that have stack unwinding, where every function call is a potential early return.
[src:linear-types/substructural-type-system] However, as a close analogy, the semantic of implicitly inserted destructor calls can be restored with deferred function calls.
[src:linear-types/substructural-type-system] Under the resource interpretation, a *normal* type does not restrict how many times a variable can be moved from.
[src:linear-types/substructural-type-system] C++ (specifically nondestructive move semantics) falls in this category.
[src:linear-types/uniqueness-type] In computing, a **unique type** guarantees that an object is used in a single-threaded way, with at most a single reference to it.
[src:linear-types/uniqueness-type] If a value has a unique type, a function applied to it can be optimized to update the value in-place in the object code.
[src:linear-types/uniqueness-type] Such in-place updates improve the efficiency of functional languages while maintaining referential transparency.
[src:linear-types/uniqueness-type] Unique types can also be used to integrate functional and imperative programming.
[src:linear-types/uniqueness-type] Uniqueness typing is best explained using an example.
[src:linear-types/uniqueness-type] Now `doImperativeReadLineSystemCall` reads the next line from the file using an OS-level system call which has the side effect of changing the current position in the file.
[src:linear-types/uniqueness-type] But this violates referential transparency because calling it multiple times with the same argument will return different results each time as the current position in the file gets moved.
[src:linear-types/uniqueness-type] This in turn makes `readLine` violate referential transparency because it calls `doImperativeReadLineSystemCall`.
[src:linear-types/uniqueness-type] The `unique` declaration specifies that the type of `f` is unique; that is to say that `f` may never be referred to again by the caller of `readLine2` after `readLine2` returns, and this restriction is enforced by the type system.
[src:linear-types/uniqueness-type] And since `readLine2` does not return `f` itself but rather a new, different file object `differentF`, this means that it's impossible for `readLine2` to be called with `f` as an argument ever again, thus preserving referential transparency while allowing for side effects to occur.
[src:linear-types/uniqueness-type] Uniqueness types are implemented in functional programming languages such as Clean, Mercury, SAC and Idris.
[src:linear-types/uniqueness-type] They are sometimes used for doing I/O operations in functional languages in lieu of monads.
[src:linear-types/uniqueness-type] A compiler extension has been developed for the Scala programming language which uses annotations to handle uniqueness in the context of message passing between actors.
[src:linear-types/uniqueness-type] A unique type is very similar to a linear type, to the point that the terms are often used interchangeably, but there is in fact a distinction: actual linear typing allows a non-linear value to be typecast to a linear form, while still retaining multiple references to it.
[src:linear-types/uniqueness-type] Uniqueness guarantees that a value has no other references to it, while linearity guarantees that no more references can be made to a value.
[src:linear-types/uniqueness-type] Linearity and uniqueness can be seen as particularly distinct when in relation to non-linearity and non-uniqueness modalities, but can then also be unified in a single type system.
